page.title: 05Holwell - Ecology
page.content:
There are large areas of woodland - mostly oak, ash, birch, chestnut, Scots pine and spruce fir. Roe deer, fox and badger abound. Rabbit, hare, stoat, weasel and grey squirrel are common. The woods are full of bluebells, primroses, wood anemones, snowdrops, and wild daffodils. Butterflies are numerous. No longer rare are the clouded yellow, comma, silver-washed fritillary and white admiral. The birds include cuckoo, fly- catcher, nightingale, blackcap, heron, buzzard, kingfisher, kestrel and sparrowhawk. There is one rookery of 40 nests.
